  <article xml:id="session3wks" label="3333">
    <title>MATH 142 Hands-On, Grades Up</title>
    <introduction>
    <p>
     For workspace between exercises, print this worksheet or download to your device by clicking the printer icon.
    </p>
    </introduction>
<!--START TYPING CONTENT FOR SESSION BELOW HERE-->
<worksheet>
    <title> Session #3 (Sections 1.1-1.4, 2.1)</title><!-- SECTION 1-->
    <p>
      Directions: Answer each of the following as best you can. Feel free to discuss your thoughts about the questions with some peers around you. 
      For additional practice problems and explanations, refer to the Math 142 textbook which is free and can be downloaded as a PDF 
      at <url href="https://oaktrust.library.tamu.edu/items/03980291-5e85-4d2e-a742-961ac49666aa"> Texas A&amp;M The OAKTrust Digital Repository </url>.
    </p>
    
      <paragraphs>
        <title>Getting Warmed Up and in the Right Mindset</title>
    <exercise workspace="0.4in"><!-- #1 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
          State the formula for finding the average rate of change of a function <m>f</m> on the interval <m>[a,b]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is also known as the slope of the <fillin/> line.
        </p>
      </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="0.5in"><!-- #2 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
         Find the average rate of change of <m>\displaystyle f(x)=x^{2}+5x</m> on the interval <m>\displaystyle [2,3]</m>.
         Draw the line that represents this average rate of change on the graph. 
        </p>
        <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session3_Fig2.png" width="50%">
          <shortdescription>Graph of a function plotted on the coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more details.</shortdescription>
          <description>
            <p>
              Graph of an upward open parabola, labeled <m>f(x)=x^2+5x</m> plotted on the coordinate axes. The points <m>(2, 14)</m> and <m>(3, 24)</m> are labeled on the graph.
            </p>
          </description>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="0.5in"><!-- #3 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
        State the formula for the difference quotient of a function <m>f</m> at <m>x = a</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="1in"><!-- #4 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
         Compute the difference quotient of <m>f(x) = \sqrt{x}</m> at <m>x = 4</m> with <m>h = 0.1</m>.
         (Round your answer to four decimal places, if needed).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
   </paragraphs> 
    
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Let Us Get Our Hands On</title>
    <exercise number="1"><!-- #1 -->
      <introduction>
        <p>
          The cost of a company to produce <m>x</m> products is given by <m>C(x) = 0.04x^{2}+130</m> dollars.
        </p>
      </introduction>
            <task>
              <introduction>
                <p>
                  Calculate the average rate of change of cost on each of the following intervals.
                </p>
              </introduction>
                  <task workspace="1in">
                    <p>
                      <m>[95,100]</m>
                    </p>
                  </task>
                  <task workspace="1in">
                    <p>
                      <m>[97,100]</m>
                    </p>
                  </task>
                  <task workspace="1in">
                    <p>
                      <m>[99,100]</m>
                    </p>
                  </task>
                  <task workspace="1in">
                    <p>
                      <m>[100,101]</m>
                    </p>
                  </task>
            </task>
            <task workspace="2in">
              <p>
                Use part (a) to approximate the instantaneous rate of change of cost when <m>100</m> products are produced.
                Interpret your results.
              </p>
            </task>
    </exercise> 
    <exercise number="2"><!-- #2 -->
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Suppose we want to find the instantaneous rate of change of <m>f(x)=x^{2}+5x</m> at <m>x=3</m>:
        </p>
      </introduction>
            <task>
              <p>
                Circle the correct formula for calculating the instantaneous rate of change of <m>f</m> at <m>x = 3</m>:
                <md>
                  m = \lim_{h \to 3}\frac{f(3+h)-f(3)}{h}\quad \quad \text{OR}\quad \quad m = \lim_{h \to 0}\frac{f(3+h)-f(3)}{h}
                </md>
              </p>
            </task>

            <task>
              <introduction>
                <p>
                  Follow the steps below to compute <m>m</m>.
                </p>
              </introduction>
                  <task workspace="1in">
                    <p>
                      Calculate <m>f(3+h)</m> and combine like terms.
                    </p>
                  </task>

                  <task workspace="1in">
                    <p>
                      Calculate <m>f(3+h)-f(3)</m> and combine like terms.
                    </p>
                  </task>

                  <task workspace="1in">
                    <p>
                      Calculate the difference quotient <m>\frac{f(3+h)-f(3)}{h}</m> and simplify to get rid of <m>h</m> on the bottom.
                    </p>
                  </task>

                  <task workspace="1in">
                    <p>
                      Take the limit <m>h \to 0</m> of your simplified expression in iii.
                      Label the resulting value as <m>m</m>.
                    </p>
                  </task>
            </task>
    </exercise>
  
  
    <exercise workspace="1in" number="3"><!-- #3 -->
      <statement>
        <p> In #2 we found that the instantaneous rate of change of <m>f</m> at <m>x = 3</m> is <m>m=11</m>.
          Use this to find the equation of the line tangent to <m>f(x)</m> at <m>x=3</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
    <exercise workspace="6in" number="4"><!-- #4 -->
      <statement>
        <p> Find the instantaneous rate of change of <m>\displaystyle f(x)=2\sqrt{x}</m> at <m>x=4</m>.
        <em>Hint: Follow the same steps as in #2.
        Multiply by the conjugate in step iii and simplify.
        If you don't do this, then taking the limit <m>h \to 0</m> in step iv.
        gives you the indeterminate form <m>\frac{0}{0}</m> which we can't work with.</em>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
  
  
    <exercise workspace="1in" number="5"><!-- #5 -->
      <statement>
        <p> Find the equation of the line tangent to <m>f(x) = 2\sqrt{x}</m> at <m>x=4</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
  
  
    <p>
      Use the graph of <m>p(x)</m> below to answer questions #6-7.
    </p>
    <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session3_Fig6.png" width="70%">
          <shortdescription> Graph of a function plotted on coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
          <description>
            <p>
              Graph of a piecewise function <m>p(x)</m> plotted on coordinate axes.
              Starting from the bottom left, the graph increases to the point <m>(4,18.34)</m> where it is very steep and almost appears vertical around <m>x=-6</m>.
              The graph is then linear and decreases from <m>(4,18.34)</m> to <m>(8,2.34)</m>.
              The graph then picks up again at <m>(8,10.25)</m> where it increases and approaches, but doesn't touch, the vertical asymptote <m>x=10</m> until it
              leaves the coordinate axes. 
              The graph then decreases coming from the right side of the vertical asymptote and approaches, but doesn't touch, the horizontal asymptote <m>y=10</m>
              until it leaves the coordinate axes.
            </p>
          </description>
    </image>

    <exercise number="6"><!-- #6 -->
      <introduction>
        <p> 
          Find the following limits.
        </p>
        </introduction>
            <task>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x\rightarrow -4} p(x)}</m>
              </p>
            </task>

            <task>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x\rightarrow 2} p(x)}</m>
              </p>
            </task>

            <task>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x\rightarrow 10^-} p(x)}</m>
              </p>
            </task>

            <task>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x\rightarrow 8^+} p(x)}</m>
              </p>
            </task>

            <task>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} p(x)}</m>
              </p>
            </task>

            <task>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} p(x)}</m>
              </p>
            </task>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise workspace="1.5in" number="7"><!-- #7 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find all <m>x-</m>values where <m>p(x)</m> is discontinuous.
          For each <m>x-</m>value, state the condition (I, II, or III) within the definition of continuity that fails first.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise number="8"><!-- #8 -->
      <introduction>
        <p> 
         Estimate the following limits numerically by building a table with at least 3 <m>x</m>-values approaching the given <m>x</m>-value.
        If the limit does not exist, state so and and use limit notation to describe any infinite behavior.
        Round to four decimal places if necessary.
        </p>
      </introduction>
          <task workspace="3in">
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to \frac{3}{2}^+}\frac{4x^{2}-2x-6}{2x-3}</m>
            </p>
          </task>

          <task workspace="3in">
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to 1}\frac{x^{2}}{x-1}</m>  <em>Hint: Create two tables.</em>
            </p>
          </task>
    </exercise> 

  </paragraphs>
  
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Now Grades Go Up</title>
      <exercise workspace ="1in" number="1"><!-- #1 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            Determine whether <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x\rightarrow -1} \frac{1}{x^{2}-1}}</m> exists.
            If it does exist, find the limit.
            If it does not exist, describe the behavior of the function at <m>x=-1</m>.
              <ol marker="(a)">
                <li> <p>The limit exists, and it equals <m>0</m>.</p> </li>
                <li> <p> The limit exists, and it equals <m>\displaystyle -\frac{1}{2}</m>.</p> </li>
                <li> <p>The limit exists, and it equals <m>1</m>. </p> </li>
                <li> <p> The limit does not exist, but <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x \rightarrow -1^-} f(x) \rightarrow \infty}</m> and
                  <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x \rightarrow -1^+} f(x) \rightarrow -\infty}</m>.</p> </li>
                <li> <p> The limit does not exist, but <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x \rightarrow -1^-} f(x) \rightarrow -\infty}</m> and
                  <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x \rightarrow -1^+} f(x) \rightarrow \infty}</m>.</p> </li>
              </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace ="1in" number="2"><!-- #2 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\rightarrow 5}\frac{x^{2}-x-20}{x^{2}-25}</m>.
              <ol marker="(a)">
                <li> <p> <m>0</m> </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>1</m> </p> </li>
                <li> <p> DNE </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle \frac{4}{5}</m> </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle \frac{9}{10}</m> </p> </li>
              </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise workspace ="1in" number="3"><!-- #3 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the horizontal asymptotes for <m>\displaystyle f(x)=\frac{6e^{-x}+8e^{-3x}+6}{7e^{-2x}-2+2e^{-3x}}</m>
              <ol marker="(a)">
                <li> <p> <m>f(x)</m> does not have any horizontal asymptotes. </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>f(x)</m> has two horizontal asymptotes at <m>y=-3</m> and <m>y=4</m>. </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>f(x)</m> has only one horizontal asymptote at <m>y=-3</m>. </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>f(x)</m> has only one horizontal asymptote at <m>y=0</m>. </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>f(x)</m> has only one horizontal asymptote at <m>y=4</m>. </p> </li>
              </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace ="1in" number="4"><!-- #4 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the intervals where <m>f(x)</m> is continuous.
            <md>
              f(x)= \left\{ \begin{array}{lc}\displaystyle{\frac{x^{2}-9}{x-3}} &#x26; x &#x3C; 4\\ &#x26; \\ \displaystyle{\sqrt{10x+9}} &#x26; x > 4 \\\end{array} \right.
            </md>
              <ol marker="(a)">
                <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle (-\infty, 3) \cup (3,\infty)</m> </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle (-\infty, 3) \cup (3, 4) \cup (4,\infty)</m> </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle (-\infty, 4) \cup (4,\infty)</m> </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle (-\infty, \infty)</m> </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle (-\infty, -\frac{9}{10}) \cup (-\frac{9}{10}, 3) \cup (3,4) \cup (4,\infty)</m> </p> </li>
              </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace ="1in" number="5"><!-- #5 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose for some function <m>g(x)</m>, you know <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x\rightarrow 8^-} g(x) \rightarrow -\infty}</m>.
            What can you conclude happens at <m>x=8</m>?
              <ol marker="(a)">
                <li> <p> <m>g(x)</m> has a vertical asymptote at <m>x=8</m>.</p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>g(x)</m> has a horizontal asymptote at <m>x=8</m>. </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>g(x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=8</m>. </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>g(x)</m> has a hole at <m>x=8</m>. </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>g(8) \rightarrow \infty</m> </p> </li>
              </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace ="1in" number="6"><!-- #6 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            Given <m>\displaystyle p(x)=\frac{7x(x+8)(x+1)^{2}}{5x^{2}(x+1)(x+8)^{2}}</m>, find <em>all</em> vertical asymptotes for <m>p(x)</m>.
              <ol marker="(a)">
                <li> <p> <m>x=0</m>, <m>x=-1</m>, and <m>x=-8</m>  </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>x=-1</m> </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>x=-1</m> and <m>x=-8</m> </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle y=\frac{7}{5}</m>. </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>x=0</m>, <m>x=-8</m> </p> </li>
              </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace ="1in" number="7"><!-- #7 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            Given <m>\displaystyle p(x)=\frac{7x(x+8)(x+1)^{2}}{5x^{2}(x+1)(x+8)^{2}}</m>, 
            find the <m>x-</m>values where <em>all holes</em> occur for <m>p(x)</m>.
              <ol marker="(a)">
                <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle x=-1</m> and <m>\displaystyle x=-8</m> </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle x=0</m>, <m>\displaystyle x=-1</m>, and <m>\displaystyle x=-8</m> </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle x=-1</m> </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle x=0</m> and <m>\displaystyle x=-8</m></p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>p(x)</m> does not have any holes. </p> </li>
              </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise number="8"><!-- #8 -->
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Determine whether each statement is true or false.
          </p>
        </introduction>
                <task> <p> True/False: If <m>g(x)</m> is a rational function with <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to \infty}g(x) = -\frac{1}{2}</m>, 
                  then it must be that <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to -\infty}g(x) = -\frac{1}{2}</m>. </p> </task>
                <task> <p> True/False: If <m>h(x)</m> is a rational function with <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to \infty}h(x) \to -\infty</m>, 
                  then it must also be that <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to -\infty}h(x) \to -\infty</m>.</p> </task>
                <task> <p> True/False: If <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 4}f(x) = -7</m>, then it must also be that <m>f(4) = -7</m>. </p> </task>
      </exercise>
 </paragraphs>

</worksheet>

  </article>

